<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96706906425252></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96706906425252><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=96706906425252>Pet Weapons - what to use and when.</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=96706906425252#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=666><span id=Scholar>Zyphyr</span></a>, <span id=Scholar>Scholar</span><br><span id=notbold>91 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Aug 23rd 6:17 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.60]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>There a several reasons to give weapons to a pet:<br>A) Increasing the maximum damage of the pet.<br>B) Enabling low level pets to hit magic-only creatures.<br>C) Enabling Dual Wield<br>D) The weapon has a proc that you want the pet to take advantage of.<br>Until they enabled weapon wielding for mage pets there was an E - reducing pet attack delay. That doesn't work anymore.<br><br>If you want to increase a pets max damage, you need to hand it a weapon which has a damage rating more than 50% of the pets current damage. A pets maximum damage is the higher of its normal max and double the damage rating of the weapon it is wielding.<br><br>For pets below level 12, if you want it to hit magic-only mobs (like will-o-wisps) you need to give the pet a magic weapon. Fortunately, every weapon we summon is magic.<br><br>To enable dual wield, just hand the pet any two 1 handed weapons.<br><br>For procs - hand the pet a weapon with a proc (duh!).<br>--<br>At level 4, if you can dig up a Rusty 2HS give it to your pet - the 9 damage rating will boost max damage to 18.<br><br>At 8, the rusty 2-hander is still good, unless you are trying to hunt wisps. If you don't have a rusty 2H, or are hunting wisps, give your pet a Staff of Tracing. The staff will bost max damage to 14 (the inherent max for level 8 pets ranges from 8 to 14), and the pet can hit magic.<br><br>At 12 the pet gains the ability to hit magic inherently, and only the lower half of the summons will benefit from the staff of tracing. They all will still benefit from a 2-handed sword.<br><br>At 16, the lower 2 summons will benefit from a staff of warding (boosts max to 16), while the lower 3 will benefit from the rusty.<br><br>At 20, the bottom pet will gain from the staff, and the lower 2 will benefit from the sword.<br><br>At 24, pets can start dual wielding, and now do enough damage that none of our summoned weapons or a 2-handed sword will increase the max. At this point use a pair of summoned daggers to enable dual wield.<br><br>At 29+, there is nothing better than dual swords of runes for your pet.<br><br>The information above assumes that you are providing the weapons yourself.<br><br>One alternate option I have seen from time to time is giving gnoll-hide lariats to pets for ht stun effect. A high level air pet wielding a pair of lariats can keep a mob stunned for a truly obscene percentage of the fight.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>Zyphyr Runnersbane<br>60th Vending Machine<br>Cult of the Ancient Wyrm<br>Solusek Ro<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
